The call to Object>>getDepListAndAddPathTerm:withIVOffset:logging: is made from PathTerm>>addMappingsForObject:logging: ... the error is emanating from IdentityIndex>>traverse:upTo: which is only called in the second branch ... 
--------------------
--------------------
--------------------
--------------------
My guess at this point is that the problem has to do with the call to IdentityIndex>>_findFirstUnsharedPathTerm in the beginning of IndexManager>>_addMappingsFor:on: ... Once an index has been added the \"shared
pathTerms\" are expected to have been already taken care of, but in the case of the 
invariant object we are skipping the creation of dependencies ... presumably this would break for another equality index that \"shared\" the pathterms.

BTW, I am suspicious that we appear to be skipping creating dependencies for all of the children as well ... the skipping of creating dependencies should only be done for leaf terms! I also believe that this bug should be restricted to identity 
indexes...a second equality index with a shared path should fail as well.

Second equality index is failing as well:

  ./bug -ci --nsc=createNsc --equality path1.value1 path1.path2.value1

this should work:

  ./bug -ci --nsc=createNsc --modify=variant --equality path1.path2.value1

while this will fail, becuase of missing dependencies (BUT IT DOES NOT!):

  ./bug -ci --nsc=createNsc --modify=invariant --equality path1.path2.value1

so the dependents are correctly calculated and we are down to the two failure modes:

  ./bug -ci --nsc=createNsc --identity --equality
  ./bug -ci --nsc=createNsc --equality path1.value1 path1.path2.value1

and they are breaking because of traversal issues.
--------------------
--------------------
It looks like PathTerm>>_ivOffsetFor: can be used if we are missing the deplist (when the object is invariant) ...

Given the expense of doing the lookup (instance variable name to offset) it may actually be a better idea to go ahead and put invariant objects into the dependency list ... if they are not the last term ...
